Struggling with Ankle Mobility? SAVE THIS SEQUENCE

I’ve kept it short, but by no means is this an exhaustive list. 

Sequence duration/reps etc below:

Exercise 1: I like to start with 5-10 minutes of foam rolling. Not because it’s going to yield a permanent tissue change, but it can facilitate temporary shifts in mobility/range that we can make use of in the sequence. 

Exercise 2: I will always perform PAILs, RAILs and other forms of Passive into PNF holds from this position (if you’re unsure of what those are check my mobility programme or YouTube channel). If you do get pinching at the front, I highly recommend placing a block under your toes. 1 minute passive hold, vs. 10 seconds PAILs and 10 seconds RAILs x 3 sets.

Exercise 3: Eccentrically loading the calf muscles to build strength at that end range. 20 reps each side, 1-2 sets. 

Exercise 4: CARs (Controlled Articular rotations) are not so much for increasing range (the others do that) but these help you to ensure that you have control over the joint. More on this on my YT channel and the mobility programme. 

This isn’t an exhaustive list of exercises, but I find what people most struggle with when it comes to ankle mobility is, well, firstly, not doing anything about it (lol, me too) and secondly, not performing a mix of static vs. active vs. dynamic stretches/mobility drills.

Still confused about training around your period? 

Here are three things I do to modify my training BEFORE menstruation.

1. HYDRATION - core body temperature rises after ovulation during the luteal phase increasing the need for water. Dehydration increases blood viscosity which makes everything harder (including exercise, cognition AND regulating body temp).

2. Reduce the load I lift, but I don’t increase the reps. I focus mostly on technique and mobility. This is what I do the week before not the day I bleed. Usually during my period, I am actually quite strong and there is good reason for that - check the caption. 

3. Increase low-intensity, steady state cardio - especially walking. Not only is it good for mental health (during what can be a potentially sensitive time) but it also helps to massage the ascending and descending colon which helps ease any digestive traffic jams I got going on prior to menstruation. (I also walk on my period too to help with menstrual cramping). 

Everyone’s experience is different and our perception is impacted by our peers and societal messaging - the most important thing is to check in with your own experience.

A few extra things to note:
Hormonally speaking we are actually in great shape to be lifting or working at greater intensities during our period. HOWEVER - as someone who bleeds a lot, there are certain logistic involved that make me NOT want to lift at greater intensities on day 1. However by day 3 I am GREAT and can comfortably get back into training to work hard. Please check out @drstacysims , @doclyssfitness and @larabriden for much more on your cycle and female health. Feel free to tag anyone I’m not tagging who shares qualified, researched information on training with their cycle.

10 Minute Shoulder Mobility Routine - that actually works 🙏🏾 (but you have to save it and do it consistently) 

This sequence is for anyone who has heavily neglected shoulder mobility; I’m looking at all fighters, gym bros and anyone who has neglected their shoulder mobility really. 

The sequence explained below 👇🏽 

1. Hold each side for 30-60s in the forward fold. 

2. Hold each variation for 60s then finish with a 10 second isometric contraction in both directions (PAILs and RAILs*👇🏽).

3. Again, passive hold at your passive range (relaxed), then 10s activation/ contract in the progressive angle, 10s in the regressive angle. Then perform your passive hold again (hopefully slightly deeper)

4. This internal rotation capsule stretch is intense. Take it slow and if it’s your first time, just perform the passive stretch hold only and build up to your active PAILs and RAILs. 

5. Controlled articular rotations, 10 each side. 

*PAILs = progressive angular isometric loading
RAILs = regressive angular isometric loading. It was coined by the Functional Range Conditioning specialists ❤️ and it is also used under different names by gymnasts, martial artists and other stretch experts.

If you’re feeling down about your body (it’s form or function - READ THIS). 

It’s bit of a caption … like old times, when I used to post pictures and write things, but hopefully you’ll find it helpful.

In eastern philosophies there has always been and reminder that over identifying with and over-attaching to the body is a major cause of suffering.

Instead, these philosophies encourage that you see the body as a tool for enlightenment and awakening. Something that should be nurtured and nourished, while still acknowledging its transient nature (after all the human body is a part of nature).

Now, even if you can’t get on board with the idea of ‘enlightenment’ I think there is something very powerful about remembering that the body serves as a vehicle for us to explore and expand in our lives - not just as a mechanism for being accepted in this society.

It’s not easy to do because, not only is appearance and physical over-identification really really (really) reinforced on visual platforms like instagram, but they are also deeply engrained in our more primal psychology (bigger lips, boobies and butts are all cues for things of a more primal nature).

The reason that I have always wanted to include Yoga, meditation (and even philosophy) INTO my fitness practice (which is what the Vertue Method approach is), is because if it’s JUST fitness, if it’s JUST dieting, the likelihood of you developing an over-identification with your body and it’s appearance (and even function) is high and will lead to mental health issues down the line. You don’t have to take my word for it - it’s in the research and it’s in the anecdotal accounts of SO MANY fitness professionals and athletes.

and even though I teach and practice yoga, I am NOT immune to these negative feelings. It requires repetition and daily reminders of a deeper worth - who you are to your family, your children, that friend in need - rather than the ephemeral and ever changing physical aspects / forms and even functions of your body.

SHOULD YOU EXERCISE IN THE MORNING? 

In my experience clients who trained with me in the mornings were the most consistent when I compared them those who trained at lunch or in the evenings and this was usually down to the fact that nothing would get in the way of their schedule if they had it locked in the mornings (other than sickness or child illness). This included mums who were able to get time away from kids if they trained at 6am - obviously this is not feasible for everyone (this is where the VM home workouts are an absolute god send btw - because you don’t have to leave the house - you just hit play and we train together). 

Please remember that this research review was not a meta-analysis so we’re not obtaining statistically significant results here. 

One of the limitations of this review, as pointed out by the researchers, is that more research is needed in free-living environments - rather than highly controlled supervised exercise training to determine just how effective morning timing is when not controlled. 

Conversely, another issue is that all the data in this review is correlational, and there is a need for more studies (RCTs) to determine whether exercise timing has a causal relationship with exercise behaviour, as well as short and longer term weight loss.

Journalling is a huge part of the VM Sculpt programme because the thing that is often keeping you from results is:
- not motivation
- not discipline
- not a lack of confidence. 
But instead, a lack of introspection. 

The journal prompts in the programme are designed to be done at the end of every week to reflect on your experiences, emotions and more importantly appraisals of those events - so that you can come to understand your core beliefs WHICH ARE SHAPING your behaviour (mostly unconsciously). 

Here are 3 questions that you could use as journal prompts to get curious about your uncertainty appraisal

- What is the most pressing ‘uncertainty’ belief that you have active in your mind right now?
- Describe an uncertain situation that triggers this belief for you. How does the uncertainty make you feel?
- If you couldn’t avoid this situation, what would you do to cope with it?

Finally remembering that thoughts are not facts can be another powerful way to reframe any fears you have. 

This task is purely about getting curious - it’s not designed to FIX anything, it’s simply to become more aware. If you have the money and/or time to speak with a therapist, AMAZING. Otherwise use them as a mechanism for tracking your emotions over time. 

I am not a therapist (yet), this is not the ONLY approach to these feelings - but they are rarely discussed in the fitness space - hence my desire to bring light to these. Psychologists and therapists I really welcome your thoughts and comments on Intolerance of Uncertainty ❤️‍🩹

**Why do I do these exercises?**

- They are fun and super challenging core and ab exercises

- I can simultaneously strengthen my upper body, especially shoulders. Which makes my time in the gym more efficient.

- They have great transference into handstand / gymnastics work

- The last two really keep me honest regarding my hip and hamstring flexibility.

**How should you approach it?**

get comfortable with the first exercise for 4 weeks, see if you can progress to the second building on your repetitions. When you feel comfortable with both you’ll be able to progress to the final exercise which is a tricky combination of the two. 

**Sets and Reps:**

Obviously this depends but I try to opt for 3 sets of 10-15 reps of the hardest variation (which actually means you end up doing double because 1 rep is equal to the bent knee pike, into the straight leg pike, back to the bent knee pike).

HOW TO COOK THE TOFU:

Ingredients:

- 1 block (about 14 ounces) extra-firm tofu
- 1 good spray of olive oil
- 1 tablespoon cornstarch (optional but worth it)
- 1 teaspoon honey
- 2 tablespoons soy

1. **Drain the tofu.** Wrap your tofu in a clean tea towel and place under some heavy items like a chopping block with some thick recipe books on top (that’s how I do it). Let the tofu drain for at least 15-30 minutes. Meanwhile, heat your oven to 200°C

2. **Cut the tofu.** Once the tofu has drained, remove the weights and tea towels. Slice it in the middle first, then into 3 X 3 slices horizontally and then vertically.

3. **Coat the tofu.** Add your tofu to a large mixing bowl. Spray with olive oil, and toss until evenly coated. Sprinkle evenly with soy, honey and cornstarch. Gently toss until the tofu is evenly coated.

4. **Arrange on a baking sheet.** Turn the tofu out onto a parchment-covered baking sheet, and arrange it so that the tofu is in an even layer (not touching).

5. **Bake until crispy.** Bake for 15 minutes. Then remove the baking sheet from the oven, and flip each of the tofu bites so that they can cook evenly on the other side. Return to the oven for 15 more minutes, or until the tofu reaches your desired level of crispiness. 

6. **Enjoy now or store for later.**

COULD STRETCHING MAKE YOU FITTER? 

Yes, physical activity shows similar benefit towards vascular function and arterial stiffness (1) - however, there are obviously many different benefits for developing a stretch practice that aren’t supported by physical activity alone (if we’re not including stretching as physical activity). Aside from increasing range of motion stretching can help to reduce stress and promoting relaxation. When combined with regular exercise, stretching can help improve overall physical fitness and performance.

Obviously, in some cases it’s actually NOT so beneficial for performance - for example reduced range of motion in the hips may reduce the metabolic cost required to stabilise the pelvis in long-distance running (2) 

BUT if you’re not planning on making running (or powerlifting) your career anytime soon, then I would actually encourage that you dedicate some time to stretching.

If you’re a stretch hater, don’t worry - I feel you. I don’t get anywhere near as much joy from stretching as I do from ‘the pump’ I get in the gym. However, avoiding it is only going to cost me both long-term and short term. 

More notes from the study below (references in comments):

”- Vascular function, arterial stiffness and vascular remodelling were evaluated before and after

- 12 weeks of passive stretching training and after 6weeks from training cessation, in the femoral, popliteal (treated with stretching), and brachial arteries (untreated) of both sides.

- After passive stretching training, vascular function and arterial remodelling improved, and arterial stiffness decreased in all the arteries, suggesting modifications of both central and local blood flow control mechanisms. Passive stretching-induced improvements related to central mechanisms seemed to have a short duration, as they returned to pre-training baseline within 6 weeks from training cessation, whereas those more related to a local mechanism persisted in the follow-up.”

Behavioural Activation Theory, which is backed by a whole bunch of empirical evidence, very simply explores the fact that our behaviour has HUGE implications on our mood. More specifically, it looks at how events that send us into a depressive state might cause us to REDUCE behaviours that are good for us (physical activity, time in nature, time with close friends) and simultaneously undertake avoidance type behaviours (eg. not seeing friends, staying home, reducing physical activity to numb out on TV), which in turn continue to make our mood even lower. This ultimately leads to a vicious cycle. 

Now I want to make it clear that I am not trying to address depression or depressive symptoms in this post (for reasons such as; I am not qualified to and the theory, like all theories has limitations for all the different reasons we can experience depression). 

I am simply drawing some inspiration from this theory to help address some concepts around MOTIVATION - something that many of us are constantly grappling with when it comes to training. 

I’m going into MUCH more detail in my email this week so if you’re keen to understand more, or you want to read some of the literature on it - all the references and articles worth reading will be in that email.

3 things you should know about pain (the 2nd one is kind of depressing - but still worth knowing) 

Recently at uni, I had my whole world turned upside down when I learned about pain (and nociception - the sensory nervous system’s process of encoding harmful stimuli to be sent up to the brain). 

I used to believe that pain was an input, but instead I learned that pain is actually a complex output created by the brain in response to signals from the nerves. The reason it’s so complex is in part because it’s not just coming from one part of the brain; in fact - these signals pass through a few key areas including the amygdala, hypothalamus, PAG, and nucleus accumbens (NAc) - that NAc plays a role in addiction so it’s interesting but unsurprising there are some interactions with nociception.

ANYWAY - this is one of the reasons our emotional / psychological state, our sleep quality, cycle, even hydration levels can impact our pain ‘perception’ and why it differs so much from person to person. 

It’s a VERY complex topic and I don’t expect to cover all that needs to be covered in my little “3 things you should know about pain” video - 

BUT if you suffer from pain, especially chronic pain, I would recommend looking into (if you haven’t already) some of the things I bring up in the video. I’ll also chuck some good reads and references in the comments.

I have also learned so much from @yogicphysio @drmiketodorovic @louisanicola_ @wildphysiofitness (and some of my uni professors who aren’t on here) on this topic and I feel like I’ve stepped into an abyss. A fun abyss but still slightly unnerving.

SELF EFFICACY AND THE STORIES WE TELL OURSELVES 

"If you hear a voice within you say 'you cannot paint,' then by all means paint, and that voice will be silenced." - Vincent Van Gogh

Research has demonstrated that self-efficacy can be a predictor of successful behaviour change - that is to say; basically believing in yourself and your abilities is a necessary step in making changes in your life. 

Self-efficacy is defined as an individual's belief in their ability to successfully perform a specific behaviour in a given situation.

Probably the most important part of this definition is the part about 'believing in our abilities' if we want to be successful. 

Ok - so what happens if you don't believe in your abilities? 

What happens if your endeavours to make positive, healthful changes to your life are met with narratives that categorically DIS-believe?

"I always give up"

"I can't finish programmes" 

"I get bored easily and can't stay consistent"

While these may have served as observational statements at one point in your life - they only become narratives because you continue to give them attention. You continue to keep them alive. 

I have SO MANY of these and it's a constant process of slow and steady acknowledgement and elimination. But my goodness does it feel good. 

DM me if you feel like sharing the narratives you're going to let go of to allow that self-efficacy to shine through.

LOW MOTIVATION and how you can address it (using behavioural psychology)

Alrighty some extra notes on Behavioural Activation Theory (BAT) that I never have time to fit in the video :

🎭 BAT has a lot to do with response contingencies, these are often defined as the cause-and-effect relationships between our actions and the outcomes or consequences that follow, shaping our behaviour based on the results we experience. So when we have a change in these response contingencies; specifically a decrease in positive reinforcement for HEALTHY behaviours and an increase in reinforcement for UNHEALTHY behaviours - we will experience a depressed mood.

🚣🏽 Unfortunately that depressed mood, including that lull in motivation, leads to a further reinforcement of the unhealthy behaviours and less of the healthy ones. It becomes a cycle.

🛼 I don’t think this just applies to depression - so even if you don’t feel depressed or even sad, we can still see (perhaps to a lesser degree) how these behaviours become reinforced if we don’t make the decision to - as @nike says; JUST DO IT.

For those who haven’t been inundated with attachment theory (or IG and TikTok variations of it) it was originally developed by psychologist John Bowlby and posits that early life experiences with our caregivers greatly influences our emotional development and relationships throughout their lifespan. AT emphasises the importance of a secure attachment between you as a bébé and a primary caregiver (ma or pa or any one you formed a close connection with early on), which is crucial for your emotional, cognitive, and social development. Securely attached individuals typically display healthy emotional regulation and relationship skills in adulthood. In contrast, insecure attachment, categorised as either anxious, avoidant, or disorganised, can lead to various struggles in personal relationships and mental health. Essentially, attachment theory illustrates how early caregiver interactions lay the foundation for future emotional and relational patterns. 

My recent talk with @therapised was outlining this interaction between attachment styles and health outcomes, as well as what you can do about it.

More notes from the study below (references in comments):

”- Vascular function, arterial stiffness and vascular remodelling were evaluated before and after

- 12 weeks of passive stretching training and after 6weeks from training cessation, in the femoral, popliteal (treated with stretching), and brachial arteries (untreated) of both sides.

Cognitive Biases are systematic patterns of deviation from norm or rationality in judgment, where inferences about other people and situations may be drawn in a somewhat illogical fashion - and because they’re so quick we don’t even question whether they’re logic, we just behave as if they are. 

These biases are often a result of the brain's attempt to simplify information processing.

There are obviously LOADS of these badboys but the five I discuss are:

1. Anchoring Bias: This is the tendency to rely heavily on the first piece of information offered (the "anchor") when making decisions. ‘Carbs make you fat’ or ‘Weights make you bulky’ - if these were some of the first things you heard when embarking on a fitness journey - they are hard to shake. 

2. The Halo effect: Crudely put, this bias is when we trust hot people more than they perhaps deserve credit for … That was a very crude explaination and doesn’t quite hit it but I unpack a great study on this effect and how it impacted trustworthiness during the rona pano.*

3. Action Bias: This is the tendency to favor action over inaction - feel the need to constantly change things up with your programme? Yeah this little bias might be the culprit and it’s getting in the way of results.

4. The empathy gap: I loved this one the most because I make huge huge errors here. This is the bias that will have you thinking it’s perfectly fine to go over to your exes for a ‘catch-up’ convincing yourself that you definitely won’t hook up.

5. Fundamental attribution error: This is the tendency to place an undue emphasis on internal characteristics to explain someone else's behaviour in a given situation, rather than considering external factors. This one can really wreak havoc on our self-esteem and self-efficacy - how? You’ll have to listen.

Pregnancy Weight Gain - some THOUGHTS 💭 AND SOME FACTS ✅👇🏾

Unfortunately in many societies weight gain is associated with a bunch of stigma. Some of it comes from a broader societal influence and some of it originates within our own households, upbringings and experiences which ultimately interact with other psychological factors that eventually shape the views we have of the weight gain we experience in ourselves.

On the other hand, PREGNANCY weight gain tends to sit in this sort of grey area of ‘stigma’ where it’s kind of expected and yet when you’re going through it you still feel / notice the effects of this internalised stigma. 

However, this idea that we should be aiming for a skinny pregnancy (yeah I saw it on tiktok) is deeply misguided and dangerous. 

Firstly, gaining weight when you’re pregnanané is really important for the baby’s growth and development, as well as for the mother’s health during and after pregnancy.

Gaining weight during pregnancy, is not just the baby growing. There’s the weight of the baby itself, the amniotic fluid that surrounds the baby in the womb, and the placenta. Together, these account for about 38% of the weight gain.

The rest of the weight is because your body is changing – your blood volume increases (by up to 50-60% - this is wild. Vampires would love us), there’s more fluid in your body, your uterus and breasts get larger, and we store more fat. 

Most of the extra fat is stored under the skin (subcutaneous) and typically goes to places like the hips, back, and upper thighs (I have a whole bunch on the back of my arms now too). This fat storage is unique to pregnancy and starts to build up mostly in the first 30 weeks, under the influence of the hormone progesterone.*

All of this contributes to the protection of your own body and the health of your baby.

Annoyingly, I know that the effects of individual body image and weight stigma can be more powerful than a statement like; “it’s good for the health of your body and your baby.” This, coupled with the feeling of surrendering your body to a primal and natural process, completely out of your control can be incredibly disorientating.
